# SkyWeb Analytics Change Log

Detailed implementation history was moved out of `README.md` so the README can stay focused on current operation, architecture, and roadmap.

## DN-9.3 — Chart UX Polish and Runtime Hardening

- Hardened the ECharts base wrapper so charts initialize only when the DOM container is present, resize safely, and surface render failures through a reusable chart state panel.
- Added consistent chart loading, empty, and unavailable states for single-series and multi-series charts.
- Improved tooltip behavior with body-confined rendering, dashed crosshair axis pointers, latest-point filtering, and clearer value formatting.
- Standardized precision chart axis labels with adaptive date formatting, interval thinning, compact numeric labels, and safer value-range handling.
- Reduced symbol noise on dense precision charts while preserving hover behavior and latest-point emphasis.
- Extended the compatibility wrappers so chart errors/loading states can be passed through without broad page rewiring.
- Updated README, repo map, chart migration docs, chart audit docs, and transition docs to mark DN-9.3 as active.

## DN-9.2 — Chart Architecture Extraction and Adapters

- Added reusable .NET-lane chart architecture under `apps/web-dotnet/SkyWeb.Client/src/components/charts/`.
- Added `echarts/EChartBase.jsx`, `MacroLineChart.jsx`, and `MultiSeriesMacroChart.jsx`.
- Added shared chart modules for theme tokens, option builders, normalization helpers, and chart constants.
- Added thin adapter modules for indicator series, view series, dashboard chart payloads, and future alert overlays.
- Refactored `Sparkline.jsx` and `MultiSeriesSparkline.jsx` into compatibility wrappers so existing pages continue to work while the chart layer becomes reusable.
- Added `.NET-lane` ECharts base styles in `App.css`.
- Updated README, repo map, chart migration docs, and transition docs to mark DN-9.2 as the active chart architecture pass.

## DN-9.1 — ECharts + D3 Chart Engine Foundation

- Added ECharts and D3 dependencies.
- Replaced copied SVG sparkline internals in `SkyWeb.Client` with ECharts-backed single-series and multi-series charts.
- Preserved parent component APIs for `ChartPanel`, dashboard mini charts, and indicator/detail pages.
- Used D3 for value-range/tick calculations.

## DN-8 — Alerts and Signal Center in C#

- Moved alert-rule CRUD, event history, alert notifications, and Signal Center queue actions into native ASP.NET Core/C#.
- Kept alert evaluation routes proxied to SkyServer so the existing evaluator/worker remains the evaluation source of truth.

## DN-7.1 — Saved Views/Dashboards Build Stabilization

- Fixed dashboard service local variable shadowing build blocker.
- Cleared a saved-view nullable handoff warning.

## DN-7 — Saved Views and Dashboards in C#

- Moved saved-view and dashboard route families into native ASP.NET Core/C#.
- Preserved dashboard item support for saved-view cards and direct indicator cards.

## DN-6 — SkyWeb Profile and Preferences in C#

- Moved profile, preferences, and alert-preferences route families into native ASP.NET Core/C#.

## DN-5.2 — Indicator Series Regclass/NaN Fix

- Cast PostgreSQL `to_regclass` checks to text before Dapper/Npgsql materialization.
- Scrubbed numeric `NaN` values into JSON-safe nulls for indicator-series responses.

## DN-5.1 — Public Macro Series Stabilization

- Hardened native C# macro reads for dashboard mini-chart series.

## DN-5 — Authentication in C#

- Implemented native ASP.NET Core/C# auth endpoints for login, logout, change-password, me, and permissions.

## DN-4 — Public Macro REST Endpoints in C#

- Replaced public macro proxy endpoints with native ASP.NET Core/C# reads.

## DN-0 through DN-3 — .NET Transition Foundation

- Preserved the pre-.NET baseline.
- Created the parallel `apps/web-dotnet` lane.
- Added health, DB health, Swagger, CORS, and temporary proxy fallback.
- Wired copied `SkyWeb.Client` to `SkyWeb.Api` on port 5175.

## Phase 8 — Macro Alerts

- Added alert rules, evaluation history, triggered signal queue, app-wide signal surfacing, alert preferences, dedicated Signal Center, and alert-rule UX polish.
